explanation:
To verify the MISRA C rule about bounds when using string.h functions you must know the actual sizes and representations of the source and destination buffers, and how the record pointer is derived/validated. Specifically:

- OS_queue_prop_t (definition): the strncpy target is queue_prop->name. You need the full struct definition to learn the size and layout of the name member (and any alignment/aliasing concerns).

- OS_common_record_t (definition): the strncpy source is record->name_entry and queue_prop->creator is assigned from record->creator. You must know whether name_entry is an array embedded in the record (with a compile-time size) or a pointer to externally allocated storage and what its capacity and lifetime are.

- queue_prop->name (member size): the code computes sizeof(queue_prop->name) - 1 for the length argument to strncpy. The exact byte length of this member is required to confirm the destination bound is correct.

- record->name_entry (member type/size and null-termination guarantees): strncpy reads up to the specified number of bytes from the source. If record->name_entry is a shorter buffer or not guaranteed to contain a NUL within its allocated size, strncpy could read beyond its bounds. You must know the source buffer capacity and whether the implementation guarantees NUL-termination.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro/inline helper) and OS_global_queue_table (table declaration): these determine how record is obtained (indexing, pointer arithmetic) and whether the returned record pointer points to a valid OS_common_record_t instance with a properly sized name_entry. If OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET performs casts/offsets, that can affect whether record and its members are safely addressable.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById (prototype/semantics) and OS_SUCCESS (return code): the call gate controls whether record is dereferenced. You need to know the conditions under which OS_ObjectIdGetById returns success and that the token it produces makes OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET yield a valid record for safe access.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro semantics): this macro is invoked before memset and may abort/return on NULL; understanding its behavior ensures queue_prop is valid before using sizeof(queue_prop->name) and memset.

- strncpy (standard semantics from <string.h>): to reason precisely about reads/writes you must assume the standard behavior: strncpy copies up to n bytes from source, writing NULs into the remainder of destination if source shorter, and will read up to n bytes from source (which can cause out-of-bounds reads if the source buffer is smaller than n and not NUL-terminated). Confirming this behavior is necessary to apply the MISRA rule.

- memset (standard semantics from <string.h>): used to zero the entire queue_prop object. You should confirm the size passed (sizeof(OS_queue_prop_t)) matches the actual object size and that queue_prop points to an object of that size (checked via OS_CHECK_POINTER and allocation/ownership semantics).

Collectively these symbols let an analyst determine the exact source and destination buffer sizes, pointer validity/lifetime, and whether the strncpy call can legally read the requested number of bytes without accessing beyond the bounds of record->name_entry or writing beyond queue_prop->name.
